# Second Brain — User-Level Pointer

The user keeps a personal second brain (Karpathy LLM-wiki style) at `~/second-brain/`. It's the source of truth for personal captures, journals, projects, areas, goals, knowledge notes, people, and career history. Treat it as the user's persistent memory.

The vault has its own operating contract at `~/second-brain/.claude/agents/second-brain.md` (the **second-brain** sub-agent). **Read that file** before doing anything in the vault — it defines layout, conventions, sensitivity rules, and the work-vs-personal boundary. The rules in there override anything in this pointer. Root `AGENTS.md` is a thin pointer to the same file.

## Working from outside the vault

Skills are intentionally **not** symlinked at user level (to keep every non-brain session's context small). When a trigger fires from a session whose CWD is not `~/second-brain/`:

1. **Read** the relevant skill file at `~/second-brain/.claude/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` (lookup table below). That file has the full step-by-step process.
2. The skill's instructions assume CWD = vault root. Use absolute paths or `cd ~/second-brain` before running file operations against the vault.
3. Templates live at `~/second-brain/brain/templates/`.
4. After writing into the vault, list the file paths in your reply so the user can verify.

## Triggers → Skills

| User says… | Skill at `~/second-brain/.claude/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` |
|---|---|
| "capture …", "remember this", "save to inbox", "jot this down" | `capture` |
| "process my inbox", "sort inbox", "clean inbox" | `process-inbox` |
| "weekly review", "Sunday review" | `weekly-review` |
| "journal", "daily entry", "today's entry" | `daily-journal` |
| "what do I know about X", "search my brain" | `search-brain` |
| "ingest", "distill raw/…", "process this article" | `ingest-source` |
| "lint the brain", "find orphans", "what's rotting" | `lint-vault` |
| "grill me on this plan" | `grill-me` |
| "start a new job", "bootstrap a company brain", "set up a work brain" | `bootstrap-company-brain` |
| "create a new skill" | `write-a-skill` |

Quick-lookup cheat sheet: `~/second-brain/CHEATSHEET.md`.

## Company brains (work-specific, separate)

Company-specific content does **not** belong in the personal brain. Each employer gets its own repo at `~/work/<company>/` (created by `bootstrap-company-brain`). Each company repo has its own `AGENTS.md` with **different rules** (real names allowed there; anonymization rules don't apply inside it).

Hard rule: **never write company-specific content** (employer/product/customer names, internal tools, quoted coworkers, comp/review content, business numbers, strategy/roadmap detail, credentials) into the personal brain. If the user pastes anything that looks company-specific while CWD is anywhere other than `~/work/<company>/`, pause and follow the **Sensitivity flow** in `~/second-brain/.claude/skills/capture/SKILL.md`.

## When the brain isn't installed on this machine

If `~/second-brain/` does not exist, tell the user:

> Your second brain isn't installed on this machine. Bring it up with `brain-up`:
>
> ```bash
> BRAIN_REPO=<your-brain-repo> ~/brain-up/up.sh
> ```
>
> (or scaffold a fresh one: `~/brain-up/up.sh --init --type personal --target ~/second-brain`)
>
> Then any Cursor or Claude Code session on this machine will know about it.
